<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="308" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[116,768,1455,1927]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
<emphasis box="[154,216,1456,1479]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Notes.</emphasis>
– Linnaeus’s protologue consists of a nomen specificum legitimum “ 
<taxonomicName box="[298,374,1487,1511]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Rhus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">RHUS</taxonomicName>
foliis simplicibus obovatis” followed by three synonyms, and as geographical locality “Habitat in Lombardia Italiae &amp; ad radices Apenninorum”. The first synonym “ 
<taxonomicName box="[231,319,1583,1607]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cotinus</taxonomicName>
foliis obverse ovatis” was cited from 
<bibRefCitation author="van Royen, A." journalOrPublisher="Lugduni Bata- vorum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1378" refString="van Royen, A. (1740). Florae Leydensis prodromus, exhibens plantas quae in horto academico Lugduno-Batavo aluntur. Lugduni Bata- vorum." title="Florae Leydensis prodromus, exhibens plantas quae in horto academico Lugduno-Batavo aluntur" type="book" year="1740">van Royen (1740: 243)</bibRefCitation>
and an earlier Linnaean work (
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." journalOrPublisher="Amsterdam" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1145" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1738). Hortus cliffortianus. Amsterdam." title="Hortus cliffortianus" type="book" year="1738">Linnaeus, 1738: 111</bibRefCitation>
), the second synonym “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duhamel" authorityYear="1755" box="[482,653,1647,1671]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coriaria">Cotinus coriaria</taxonomicName>
” was cited from 
<bibRefCitation author="Dodoens, R." box="[181,492,1679,1703]" journalOrPublisher="Antwerpen" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1100" refString="Dodoens, R. (1616). Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex. Antwerpen" title="Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex" type="book" year="1616">Dodoëns (1616: 778-779)</bibRefCitation>
, and the third synonym “Cocconilea s. Coccygria” from 
<bibRefCitation author="Bauhin, C." box="[454,677,1711,1735]" journalOrPublisher="Frankfurt am Main" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1084" refString="Bauhin, C. (1623). Prodromus theatri botanici. Frankfurt am Main" title="Prodromus theatri botanici" type="book" year="1623">Bauhin (1623: 415)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[116,768,1455,1927]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
<bibRefCitation author="Dodoens, R." box="[154,402,1743,1767]" journalOrPublisher="Antwerpen" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1100" refString="Dodoens, R. (1616). Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex. Antwerpen" title="Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex" type="book" year="1616">Dodoëns (1616: 778)</bibRefCitation>
provides an illustration “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duhamel" authorityYear="1755" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="coriaria">Cotinus coriaria</taxonomicName>
” that is considered original material, and could be selected as 
<typeStatus box="[235,335,1807,1831]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">lectotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[116,768,1455,1927]" lastBlockId="1.[804,1456,282,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
Among the original material there are 
<specimenCount box="[589,767,1839,1863]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
in the Clifford Herbarium at the Natural History Museum in London (BM) (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Jarvis, C." box="[367,566,1903,1927]" journalOrPublisher="Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1115" refString="Jarvis, C. (2007). Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types. Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum." title="Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types" type="book" year="2007">Jarvis 2007: 794</bibRefCitation>
). The sheet Herb. Clifford: 111, 
<taxonomicName box="[962,1042,282,305]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1042,282,305]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Cotinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1, 3A (BM [BM000558435]) bears a fragment with leaves and an inflorescence. The sheet Herb. Clifford: 111, 
<taxonomicName box="[955,1033,346,369]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[955,1033,346,369]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Cotinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1, 3B (BM [BM000558436]) bears also a fragment with leaves and an inflorescence, and the sheet Herb. Clifford: 111, 
<taxonomicName box="[1035,1117,410,433]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1035,1117,410,433]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Cotinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1, 3C (BM [BM000558437]) bears a fragment with leaves and two inflorescences.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[804,1456,282,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
On the other hand, in the Linnaean herbarium at LINN there is a sheet [Herb. Linn. N° 378.27], that bears a fragment well preserved of this species, with leaves and an inflorescence, and is annotated “ 
<collectingCountry box="[1134,1211,570,594]" name="Poland" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Polonia</collectingCountry>
” and “ 
<taxonomicName box="[1279,1361,570,594]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cotinus</taxonomicName>
” by Linnaeus. However, this sheet lacks the original Linnaean species number in the 
<emphasis box="[960,1143,634,658]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Species Plantarum</emphasis>
, in this case the number “12”, a very important link to the Linnaeus’s work, and explicitly referring to the number of the species account in Linnaeus’s protologue (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Stearn, W. T." box="[983,1141,730,754]" editor="Linnaeus, C." journalOrPublisher="Ray Society, London." pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1230" refString="Stearn, W. T. (1957). An introduction to the Species Plantarum and cognate botanical works of Carl Linnaeus. In: Linnaeus, C., Species Plantarum, A facsimile of the first edition, 1753. Vol. 1. Ray Society, London." title="An introduction to the Species Plantarum and cognate botanical works of Carl Linnaeus" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Species Plantarum, A facsimile of the first edition, 1753. Vol. 1." year="1957">Stearn, 1957</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Turland, N. J. &amp; C. E. Jarvis" box="[1159,1444,730,754]" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" pagination="457 - 485" part="46" refId="ref1340" refString="Turland, N. J. &amp; C. E. Jarvis (1997). Typification of Linnaean spe- cific and varietal names in the Leguminosae (Fabaceae). Taxon 46: 457 - 485." title="Typification of Linnaean spe- cific and varietal names in the Leguminosae (Fabaceae)" type="journal article" year="1997">Turland &amp; Jarvis, 1997</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Turland, N. J." box="[804,980,762,786]" journalOrPublisher="Willdenowia" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" pagination="303 - 309" part="36" refId="ref1302" refString="Turland, N. J. (2006). Lectotypification of Campanula saxatilis, Phy- teuma pinnatum and Verbascum arcturus, Linnaean names of three taxa endemic to Crete. Willdenowia 36: 303 - 309" title="Lectotypification of Campanula saxatilis, Phy- teuma pinnatum and Verbascum arcturus, Linnaean names of three taxa endemic to Crete" type="journal article" year="2006">Turland, 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Jarvis, C." box="[998,1140,762,786]" journalOrPublisher="Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1115" refString="Jarvis, C. (2007). Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types. Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum." title="Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types" type="book" year="2007">Jarvis, 2007</bibRefCitation>
); therefore the material is a post-1753 addition to the Linnaean collection and thus not original material for the name.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[804,1456,282,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
We have been unable to locate any further original material in any Linnaean or Linnaean–linked herbaria (e.g., in L [van Royen’s collection which is linked to the synonym by 
<bibRefCitation author="van Royen, A." journalOrPublisher="Lugduni Bata- vorum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1378" refString="van Royen, A. (1740). Florae Leydensis prodromus, exhibens plantas quae in horto academico Lugduno-Batavo aluntur. Lugduni Bata- vorum." title="Florae Leydensis prodromus, exhibens plantas quae in horto academico Lugduno-Batavo aluntur" type="book" year="1740">van Royen (1740)</bibRefCitation>
] or UPS [Burser’s collection which is linked to the Bauhin’s synonym in 1623]).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[804,1456,282,1426]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">
Among the candidate elements (specimens at 
<collectionCode box="[1325,1369,1018,1041]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bristol Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">BM</collectionCode>
and the illustration by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dodoens, R." box="[965,1142,1050,1074]" journalOrPublisher="Antwerpen" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1100" refString="Dodoens, R. (1616). Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex. Antwerpen" title="Stirpium Historiae Pempdates Sex" type="book" year="1616">Dodoëns, 1616</bibRefCitation>
), we designate the specimen at Herb. Clifford: 111, 
<taxonomicName box="[1053,1132,1082,1105]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Cotinus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1132,1082,1105]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">Cotinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1, 3 
<collectionCode box="[1175,1196,1082,1106]" country="USA" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15406" name="Harvard University - Arnold Arboretum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" type="Herbarium">A</collectionCode>
(
<collectionCode box="[1211,1256,1082,1106]" country="United Kingdom" name="Bristol Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">BM</collectionCode>
[
<specimenCode box="[1269,1441,1082,1106]" collectionCode="BM" country="United Kingdom" name="Bristol Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">BM000558435</specimenCode>
]) (image available at) as the 
<typeStatus box="[1079,1176,1114,1138]" pageId="1" pageNumber="308">lectotype</typeStatus>
. This specimen is the most complete and informative original material available and it matches Linnaeus’ protologue. Further this selection follows the practice outlined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Jarvis, C." box="[1066,1295,1210,1234]" journalOrPublisher="Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum" pageId="1" pageNumber="308" refId="ref1115" refString="Jarvis, C. (2007). Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types. Linnean Society of London &amp; British Natural History Museum." title="Order out of chaos: Linnaean plant names and their types" type="book" year="2007">Jarvis (2007: 21-22)</bibRefCitation>
wherein when both well-preserved specimens and illustrations are represented in the original material, specimens should be preferred for lectotypification because of their potential ability to provide an enormous range of additional characters (micromorphological, chemical, molecular) that cannot matched by illustration.
</paragraph>
